n=top align=left class=m><span class=title> ignorance</span><hr size=1> Some people assume that anything they want to do more then a little bit, and more then once, should be labeled an addiction, and is a bad thing. I couldn't quit EQ, not because i'm addicted, but because i really like to play so why shouldn't I?<br>
<br>
I love EQ, i've been playing for a very long time, and i play a lot.  Why? because it's what i want to do, it makes me happy, are there other things that make me happy? yes and i do them too. Some things I stopped doing, and if i missed doing them enough, i start doing them again.<br>
<br>
People who think their lives were ruined by EQ are wrong, and if it weren't for EQ they would be thinking their lives were ruined by something else. They are the people that don't really want to succeed deep down, i know this sounds crazy but it's psychologically very common. People, especially those that normally enjoy computer games are even more likely to fit this description. When you make the choice to skip class, skip work, miss a date, not do a task to play EQ you're making a choice, not someone else. It's very modern to blame our choices on something besides ourselves when it's time to face the consequences.<br>
<br>
And another thing, i'm sick of people being ashamed that they play online games. Stop feeling ashamed, it's retarded. If someone is really turned away by the fact that you enjoy online games, their loss! More people are playing online games everyday, they are mearly behind the times.  When i started playing eq i only had one friend who was into playing it, and we had a blast. Present day ALL my friends play to some degree(even the girls), and the ones who are starting now only wish that they had started sooner. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ulordmaxwell.showPublicProfile?language=EN>LordMaxwell</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/19/02 7:12:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22637.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ignorance</span><hr size=1> Cren: I'd have to say that excessive TV watching is far more of a problem than computer games. Even after you normalize for the fact that alot more people watch alot of TV.<br>
<br>
6 hours of TV a day is a sure way to a brain of mush. 6 hours of EQ a day is atleast slightly better. (As you get some real perspective on how long it takes to get rewarded. Think camping pieces for the cleric epic hurts? Just wait until you have to camp your raise. Compare this to Days of our Lives or any other daytime soap opera. People there are instantly rewarded for their actions.)<br>
<br>
You basically have to work 40 hours a week. The rest of the time you need to spend doing something that will stop you from screaming until you drown in your own blood from how mindless existence is. Welcome to hell, you get out by retiring. Then your children will keep you occupy raising their kids which they suddenly refuse to do because you have all this free time...<br>
<br>
